{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox television | show_name = Rescue Robots | image = Rescue Robots.jpg | caption = | creator = Adam Clark | director = | creative_director = | presenter = [[Anna Williamson]] | narrated = Eddie Matthews | theme_music_composer = | opentheme = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | num_series = 1 | num_episodes = 15 (of which 7 aired) | list_episodes = | executive_producer = | producer = | editor = | location = [[Pinewood Studios]] | runtime = | company = [[Tinopolis|Mentorn]] | channel = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] <!-- Original channel only --> | first_run = | first_aired = 2003 | last_aired = | related = | website = | website_title = | production_website = }}
'''Rescue Robots''' is a British [[game show]], produced by [[Tinopolis|Mentorn]] (the creators of [[Robot Wars (TV series)|Robot Wars]] and [[Techno Games]]) and shown on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in 2003, presented by [[Anna Williamson]]. One series of 15 episodes was produced but only 7 episodes were aired.
The show was based on an original idea of Adam Clark, creator of the robot 259 which featured on Robot Wars.
The set was one of the biggest sets ever built for a children's show, which included urban and industrial landscapes, countryside, lakes and rivers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rescue Robots|url=http://www.mentorninternational.com/programmes/programme-list/rescue-robots.aspx?cat=1584|publisher=Mentorn International|accessdate=6 March 2013}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
Each episode featured teams of four children using three robots best suited for the challenge. The teams had to battle against the clock in a mission to save a town called Calamity City from a disaster such as nuclear meltdown or environmental catastrophe. The tasks required a balance of problem-solving skills, driving skills and technical ability.
